==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: slue
<hw>slue</hw>
<pr>(sl⟦umac⟧)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A slough; a run or wet
place. See 2d <er>Slough</er>, 2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sloom</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Slue
<hw>Slue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Slued</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sluing</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Prov. E.
<ets>slew</ets> to turn round, Scot. to lean or incline to a side; cf.
Icel. <ets>sn<?/a</ets> to turn, bend.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>slew</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To turn
about a fixed point, usually the center or axis, as a spar or piece of
timber; to turn; -- used also of any heavy body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In general, to turn about; to twist; -- often used
reflexively and followed by <xex>round</xex>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They laughed, and <qex>slued</qex> themselves round.</q>
<rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slue</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Slue
<hw>Slue</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To turn about; to turn from the
course; to slip or slide and turn from an expected or desired course; --
often followed by <xex>round</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slue</ent>⟦br⟧

